<HEADLINE>
<P>
3RD HAITI SUICIDE CONCERNS U.S. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Washington Post 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Alarmed by three suicides in three weeks among U.S. troops in Haiti, the 
Pentagon announced Tuesday that a "combat stress action team" has arrived to 
provide counseling. 
</P>
<P>
 Pentagon officials said they don't know if the suicides are related, but the 
number of self-inflicted deaths among the roughly 20,000 personnel in Haiti is 
unusual. 
</P>
<P>
 In Somalia, where 96,000 troops served more than a year, there was one 
suicide. During the Persian Gulf War, there were 25 times more troops than in 
Haiti, but just eight suicides. 
</P>
<P>
 Two of the men in Haiti served in the same brigade of the Army's 10th Mountain 
Division. The dead included Army Pvt. Gerardo D. Luciano, 22, who died Sunday 
in Port-au-Prince. 
</P>
</TEXT>
