<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY PERSPECTIVE; BUMPS IN AN ANTI-CRIME SWEEP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With crime high on the public's list of priorities, law enforcement agencies 
have been making commendable efforts to cooperate with each other in reclaiming 
troubled neighborhoods. One such effort in Santa Ana hit a snag, however, when 
charges against six suspects apprehended during Operation Roundup, a 
high-profile drug sweep, had to be dismissed. Although having to drop the 
charges proved embarrassing, the situation offers a cautionary tale. 
</P>
<P>
 Last week, charges against four men wrongly identified as selling drugs to an 
undercover informant were dropped. The week before, a suspect was released 
after it was confirmed that he was in state prison at the time he was alleged 
to have sold drugs in Santa Ana. Previously, charges against a sixth suspect 
were dismissed after it was determined he had been misidentified. 
</P>
<P>
 Police later said that an informant sent out to buy drugs on the streets of 
Santa Ana stole from police, lied about it and helped misidentify the six who 
were later exonerated. Clearly, police, the FBI and prosecutors need to be on 
guard against unscrupulous informants and take extra care to be able to 
corroborate what informants say or do.  
</P>
<P>
 Authorities still say they believe they can successfully prosecute the more 
than 100 Operation Roundup cases now under review as a result of the 
misidentifications. According to FBI reports, the informant had been dispatched 
to build rapport with members of the Sixth Street gang, which had a grip on 
Santa Ana's 3rd Street neighborhood for years.  
</P>
<P>
 At one point last spring, the agencies actually halted the operation because 
of concerns about the informant's reliability. Prosecutors now must attempt to 
get jurors to look beyond the informant and see the larger picture of a 
troubled neighborhood. Prosecutors need to have strong cases that will hold up 
in court. 
</P>
<P>
 The cooperative effort of the FBI, Santa Ana police and the district 
attorney's office has been a worthy attempt to ease crime in a troubled 
neighborhood. The dismissals prompted a worthwhile review of all the cases in 
the gang and drug sweep, and they act as a reminder that authorities need to 
take extra care in these tricky investigations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Editorial 
</P>
</TYPE>
