<P>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL DAILY REPORT; UCLA; RECEIVER'S PERFORMANCE WAS POLISHED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JIM HODGES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wide receiver Avery Anderson, a superstitious sort, credited his nail polish 
for part of his success Saturday night, when he caught three passes for 73 
yards against Oregon State. 
</P>
<P>
 Last season, he painted his nails black before games and, when it was reported 
in a newspaper, was kidded by teammates and stopped."I hadn't painted my nails 
this season at all before Saturday," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 With right guard Matt Soenksen's return after missing two games because of an 
arch injury, the Bruins have four-fifths of their starting offensive line 
intact for the first time since the second game of the season. Only right 
tackle Paul Kennedy, who is out for the season, is missing. . . . Starting 
quarterback Wayne Cook and reserve Ryan Fien are sharing time almost equally in 
preparation for playing Arizona. . . . Linebacker Donnie Edwards leads the 
Bruins in virtually every defensive category, including tackles (66), sacks (8 
1/2), tackles for loss (13) and interceptions (2). JIM HODGES 
</P>
